{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1626"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.25,0.08,0.11,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59763"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"408"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59763"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about a red and raw area on his left leg. One month ago, he sustained a small scratch from the corner of a couch in this area on his lower leg, causing a small shallow scab which failed to heal and has since expanded to cover much of the area around his ankle. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypercholesterolaemia. He does not take any regular medications and has not engaged with the healthcare system for 15 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 89/min, blood pressure 150/98 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, temperature 37.0\u00b0C and BMI 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The ulcerated region extends up to mid-tibia and encompasses most of the lower leg (Image). The area is not sensitive to touch or noticeably warm. There are visible varicose veins bilaterally below the knee as well as extensive haemosiderin deposition. There is mild pedal oedema. Pedal pulses cannot be palpated. Capillary glucose is 12.5 mmol/L (4.0-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence oral amoxicillin/clavulanic acid","Wound swab for microscopy and culture","Commence oral flucloxacillin","Compression stocking therapy","Referral for vascular assessment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of chronic venous insufficiency leading to the formation of a venous ulcer. The image shows typical changes including lipodermatosclerosis, hyperpigmentation (haemosiderin deposition), ulceration, and visible varicose veins. The patient also has significant risk factors including diabetes, obesity, age over 70 years, and possible undiagnosed cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for vascular assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as comprehensive evaluation including ankle-brachial index and duplex ultrasound is needed before initiating definitive treatment. This will help determine if sclerotherapy or other interventions are appropriate and safe, particularly given the absent pedal pulses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression stocking therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be first-line treatment for venous insufficiency. However, it is contraindicated in this case because pedal pulses are not palpable, which raises concerns about peripheral arterial disease. Applying compression could risk limb ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was evidence of secondary cellulitis. However, the wound shows minimal evidence of infection given the lack of significant erythema or warmth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound swab for microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as there are no clinical signs of infection. Routine swabs of chronic wounds without signs of infection are not recommended as they often show colonisation rather than true infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for cellulitis caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E, but as mentioned earlier, there is minimal evidence of active infection in this wound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter vascular assessment confirms the diagnosis and excludes significant arterial disease, management options may include sclerotherapy, endovenous ablation, or surgery for the underlying venous insufficiency, along with appropriate wound care and lifestyle modifications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Venous ulcers are characterized by lipodermatosclerosis, hyperpigmentation, and location around the ankle and lower leg.","Sclerotherapy is an effective treatment for superficial venous insufficiency when confirmed by duplex ultrasound.","Compression therapy is contraindicated in venous ulcers if pedal pulses are not palpable due to risk of limb ischaemia."],"references":["Venous leg ulcers. In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. [cited 2023 Apr 8]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etg","Broom J, Woods ML. Management of bite injuries. Aust Prescr 2006;29:6-8. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2006.005","Diabetic foot infection. In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. [cited 2023 Apr 8]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etg","Huang DB, Ostrosky-Zeichner L, Wu JJ, Pang KR, Tyring SK. Therapy of common superficial fungal infections. Dermatologic Therapy. 2004;17(6):517\u201322. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15571501/","Narrow-spectrum penicillins with antistaphylococcal activity: dicloxacillin and flucloxacillin.  In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. [cited 2023 Apr 8]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etg"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19865"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19865"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbe84986-6b07-426f-95de-c01f23af80f6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cbe84986-6b07-426f-95de-c01f23af80f6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-09T08:59:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T09:02:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59763"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta"